open_comment: Conflation of the terms transgender and gender nonconforming is inaccurate and, in the eyes of some, offensive. A GNC person will never in their lives understand the struggle of being transgender, because, by definition, a GNC person is just a cis person who acts outside the norm for their gender. They don't experience things like dysphoria or the same amount of discrimination and I, among others, find it offensive to imply that it is the same thing. Regardless, the two are incredibly different and it feels as though there's not much to gain by grouping the two together.

open_comment: I was born assigned-male in 1956. By the time I was 5 years old, I was aware of wishing that I could be a girl, and I began to hate my male name - this would plague me my entire life, right up to transition at age 59. All through my teens and 20's, I was in severe depression, which I now know was gender dysphoria. From age 29 to 57, I was happily married in a very convention cis-het marriage, and I was not in gender dysphoria or depression during those years. My wife died in 2013, and within 2 months, I was cross-dressing and in severe dysphoria again, and by the late summer of 2015, I was starting to lose my sense on identity: I didn't know who I was anymore. I joined a trans support group in January 2016, found a therapist in March 2016, and committed to transition on June 4th, 2016. Everything was cleared up by my transition. No more depression, and I have found joy in my life. I have a life-partner again, (another transwoman), my daughter (she is age 40), is 100% supportive and accepting of my transition, and I have actually a much better relationship with her now than I ever did while I was trying to be her "Dad". I consider my transgender identity to be truly a gift. I have been able to experience  life on both sides of the gender line, and both phases of my life have mostly been happy.

open_comment: I'm not gender nonconforming and there was a whole group of questions that were specifically about people reacting to the gender nonconformity of the person taking the survey. I am seven years into my transition and I have been passing as a male for nearly that entire time. Not all trans people are gender nonconforming so you need to consider some kind of a "does not apply" option for those of us who are binary, cis passing, and gender conforming. open_comment: As a trans person, I still recognize biological sex as  important, real, and necessary for defining sexuality and sex based oppression. Women are oppressed for being female, homosexuals are only attracted to the same sex. I don't believe having dysphoria makes it so that transwomen can be lesbians - no male can ever be a lesbian. These beliefs make other trans people see me as "transphobic" or a "terf". But, I am still living my trans life, and experience hardship because of my choice to medically transition. I believe medical transition should be a last resort, and that's why I decided to transition. Minors should not medically transition, however. And far too many people lately are transitioning than could possibly all be actually trans. In particular there is an epidemic of homosexuals being pressured into transitioning.

open_comment: I hope you're taking well into account the different levels of experience trans members are answering this survey with. As a trans man who's been on hrt for over a year and has has my legal name changed, passing, though obviously important to me, is no longer a huge fear or worry for me because I know I completely pass now. Before hrt, my worries about passing limited my participation in events outside of my home because I was so fearful of being recognized as trans and the consequences that would follow. I used to be very miserable and low energy because fears of passing, being misgendered, and being harrassed constantly followed me. Now, I no longer have those constant worries floating around me, so I feel a lot happier and more peaceful, thanks to hrt. I hope you are taking experiences like mine into account with this survey.
